KW  - unemployment benefits
KW  - sectoral shocks
KW  - workweek restriction
AB  - The United Kingdom was depressed for 20 years between the two world wars. The decrease in output was entirely due to lower hours per worker and lower employment. Our main finding is that generous unemployment benefits, in conjunction with large negative sectoral shocks, are the most plausible candidate explanation for this depression. We also find that the conventional Keynesian monetary story for this period is unconvincing. Journal of Economic Literature Classification Numbers: E30, E24.
